# JOINS :
-- Joins are used to fetch data from multiple tables.
-- Joins are usedd whenever we want to select attribute from multiple tables.
-- There are some drawbacks of subqueries to overcome that we use joins.

# DRAWBACKS OF SUB QUERY :
1. Can't fetch data from both tables at a time
   exa: danme,ename at a time
2. If no. of conditions increases length of query also increases.
   exa:100th maxx salary.
3. Can have only 255 nested sub queries.
4. Not efficient.

#TYPES OF JOINS :
--------------------------------------
1. Cartesial join/ cross join
2. Inner join/ Equi join
3. Natural join
4. Oter join :
      i.Left outer join
      ii.Right outer join
      iii.Full outer join
5. Self join

---------------------------------------
1. CROSS JOIN :
---------------------------------------

-- Cross join is used to fetch matched and unmatched records from both the tables.
-- It is also known as Cartesian join which follows cartesian principle.
-- In cross join the records from table 1 will be merged with all records of table 2.
-- The no of column in result table = no of column in tab1 + no of col in tab2
-- The no of rows in result table = no of rows from tab1 * no of rows from tab2

# ANSI SYNTAX :
           SELECT */ DISTINCT [COLUMN_NAME]/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
           FROM TAB CROSS JOIN TAB2;

# ORACLE SYNTAX :
           SELECT */ [DISTINCT] COLUMN_NAME / EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
           FROM TABLE1, TABLE2;

-- Since, cross join produces more no of unmatched/error records and decrease efficiency we don't use cross join,
   instead of cross join we should use inner join.

---------------------------------------
2. INNER JOIN :
---------------------------------------

-- It is used to fetch matched records only.
-- To fetch only matched records we have to use join coondition.
-- It is a condition on which we merge two tables.
-- In the join condition we must we common columns.

# ANSI SYNTAX :
              SELECT */[DISTINC] COL_NAME/EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
              FROM TBA1 INNER JOIN TAB2
              ON TAB1.CC = TAB2.CC;

# ORACLE SYNTAX :
              SELECT */[DISTINC] COL_NAME/EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
              FROM TBA1, TAB2
              WHERE TAB1.CC = TAB2.CC;
1.WAQTD emp name and dept details.
--> SELECT E.ENAME, D.*
    FROM EMP E, DEPT D
    WHERE E.DEPTNO = D.DEPTNO;

2. WAQTD name, dname and loc of smith.
--> SELECT E.ENAME, D.DNAME, D.LOC
    FROM EMP E, DEPT D
    WHERE E.DEPTNO = D.DEPTNO;

3. WAQTD name, sal and loc of emp earning max sal in new yorK.
--> SELECT E.ENAME, E.SAL, D.LOC
    FROM EMP E, DEPT D
    WHERE E.DEPTNO = D.DEPTNO AND
          SAL IN ( SELECT MAX(SAL)
                   FROM EMP 
                   WHERE DEPTNO IN ( SELECT DEPTNO 
                                     FROM DEPT
                                     WHERE LOC IN 'NEW YORK' ));

4. WAQTD dname and max sal from each dept.
--> SELECT D.DNAME, SAL
    FROM DEPT D, EMP E
    WHERE D.DEPTNO = E.DEPTNO AND
          SAL IN ( SELECT MAX(SAL)
                   FROM EMP
                   GROUP BY DEPTNO );

---------------------------------------
3. NATURAL JOIN :
---------------------------------------

-- It has 2 behaviours :
1. Whenever there is relation betweeen 2 tables getting join it will act like inner join.
   exa : emp,dept
2. Whenever there is no relation between 2 tables getting join then it behaves like cross join.
   exa emp, salgrade
-- Natural join display common columns only once.

# SYNTAX :
         SELECT */[DISTINCT] COL_NMAE/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
         FROM TABL1 NATURAL JOIN TABLE2;
-- Natural join have only one syntax.

---------------------------------------
4. OUTER JOIN :
---------------------------------------

-- It is used to fetch the unmatched records from perticular table along with matched records.
-- There are 3 types of outer join : 
   i.Left outer join
   ii.Right outer join
   iii.Full outer join

i) LEFT OUTER JOIN :
-- It is used to fetch unmatched records from left table along with matched records.

# ANSI SYNTAX :
             SELECT */ DISTINCT COL/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
             FROM TABLE1 LEFT [OUTER] JOIN TABLE2
             ON TABLE1.CC = TABLE2.CC;

# ORACLE SYNTAX :
             SELECT */ DISTINCT COL/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
             FROM TABLE1, TABLE2
             WHERE TABLE1.CC = TABLE2.CC(+);

1. WAQTD name , dname of empls even though emps not working in any dept.
--> SELECT E.ENAME, D.DNAME
    FROM EMP E, DEPT D
    WHERE E.DEPTNO = D.DEPTNO(+);

ii) RIGTH OUTER JOIN :
-- It is used to fetch matched and unmatched records from right table, along with matched records from left table.

# ANSI SYNTAX :
             SELECT */ DISTINCT COL/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
             FROM TABLE1 RIGHT [OUTER] JOIN TABLE2
             ON TABLE1.CC = TABLE2.CC;

# ORACLE SYNTAX :
             SELECT */ DISTINCT COL/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
             FROM TABLE1, TABLE2
             WHERE TABLE1.CC(+) = TABLE2.CC;

1. WAQTD name , dname of empls even though DEPT not HAVING any emp working in it.
--> SELECT E.ENAME, D.DNAME
    FROM EMP E, DEPT D
    WHERE E.DEPTNO(+) = D.DEPTNO;

iii) FULL OUTER JOIN :
-- It is used to fetch the matched and unmatched records from both tables.

# ANSI SYNTAX :
             SELECT */ DISTINCT COL/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
             FROM TABLE1 FULL [OUTER] JOIN TABLE2
             ON TABLE1.CC = TABLE2.CC;

# ORACLE SYNTAX :
             SELECT */ DISTINCT COL/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
             FROM TABLE1, TABLE2
             WHERE TABLE1.CC = TABLE2.CC(+)
                        UNION
             SELECT */ DISTINCT COL/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
             FROM TABLE1 , TABLE2
             WHERE TABLE1.CC(+) = TABLE2.CC;

1. WAQTD ename, dname even empl not working in any dept or even if any dept dont have any empl working in it.
--> SELECT E.ENAME, D.DNAME
    FROM EMP E, DEPT D
    WHERE E.DEPTNO = D.DEPTNO(+)
             UNION
    SELECT E.ENAME, D.DNAME
    FROM EMP E, DEPT D
    WHERE E.DEPTNO(+) = D.DEPTNO;

---------------------------------------
5. SELF JOIN :
---------------------------------------

-- Joining table to itself is known as self join.
-- Whenever data to be displayed is from same table but present in different records then we go for self join.
-- In self join same table are merged or joined.
-- Tables must be assigned with alias name(alias are mandatory).

# ANSI SYNTAX :
             SELECT */ DISTINCT COL/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
             FROM TABLE1 [SELF] JOIN TABLE2
             ON TABLE1.CC = TABLE2.CC;

# ORACLE SYNTAX :
             SELECT */ DISTINCT COL/ EXPRESSION [ALIAS]
             FROM TABLE1 T1, TABLE1 T2
             WHERE T1.CC = T2.CC;

1. WAQTD name and mgr name of empl.
--> SELECT E.ENAME AS EMPLOYEE, M.ENAME AS MGR
    FROM EMP E, EMP M
    WHERE E.MGR = M.EMPNO;

2. WAQTD name, dname, mgrno of an emp.
--> SELECT E.ENAME AS EMP, M.ENAME AS MGR, D.DNAME
    FROM EMP E, EMP M, DEPT D
    WHERE E.MGR = M.EMPNO(+) AND
          E.DEPTNO = D.DEPTNO(+);

3. WAQTD name, dname, mgrname and mgr dname if mgr is ford.
--> SELECT E.ENAME EMP_NAME, D.DNAME EMP_DEPT, M.ENAME MGR_NAME, MD.DNAME AS MGR_DEPT
    FROM EMP E, EMP M, DEPT D, DEPT MD
    WHERE E.MGR = M.EMPNO(+) AND
          E.DEPTNO = D.DEPTNO(+) AND
          M.DEPTNO = MD.DEPTNO(+);
